[1] Pennsylvania
Date: Wed 14 Jul 2010
Source: The Mercury [edited]
<http://www.pottstownmercury.com/articles/2010/07/14/news/srv0000008828790.txt>


Dozens, perhaps hundreds, of dead fish floating
in a North Coventry pond and lying on its grassy
banks caught the eyes and noses of many in Kenilworth Park by surprise.

"I come here every week and it's incredible how
many dead fish there are ... and it's never been
like this," said [a resident] of Pottstown. "You
can smell the dead fish for sure. It's real bad."

[The man] said the last time he was at the park,
the pond looked the same as it did Tuesday [13
Jul 2010], with the exception of all the dead
fish carcasses and the pungent odor they produced.

Attempts to reach officials with North Coventry
Township were unsuccessful Tuesday.

A reporter who stopped at the township office to
speak with Township Manager Kevin Hennessey at
approximately 3:15 p.m. was told Hennessey had
left the office for the day. The reporter was
told to contact Jay Erb, the chairman of the
Parks and Recreation, by e-mail. That attempt was also unsuccessful.

A North Coventry resident said in all the years
he had been going to the park he had never seen
the conditions like they were Tuesday.

"Normally it looks like this with, the green
algae film, but I've never seen the dead fish
like this and I've been here since I'm 7 years
old," he said, recalling days of ice skating and
fishing at the pond. "I've never seen anything like this."

"I started to smell the smell, and then I got up
and walked around and I saw all these dead fish,"
the man said. "It upset me .... it blew my mind."
He guessed it could have been pollution or
perhaps something leaked into the water, noting
that "even when it got hot in years before, I've
never seen anything like this before." He said he
saw a township truck out at the park on Monday
[12 Jul 2010] and took note that the township
employee saw the dead fish, but then got into the
truck and drove away. He said he had not seen any
other activity from any township or Fish and Game officials Tuesday.

[Another 2 women] of Pottstown, said they saw the
dead fish in the pond on Sunday [11 Jul 2010].
Among the dead fish were bluegills and carp, with
at least 2 of the carp several feet in length.

[One of the women], who is studying environmental
sciences, said she thought the problem may have
been a lack of oxygen in the water caused by the
recent heat wave. "We've been up there before and
I've never seen anything like that," she said
[and noted] that there was a man at the pond both
Sunday and Monday [11-12 Jul 2010] wearing a
wildlife management shirt who she believed to be
a park ranger. She said the man commented that he
didn't know how they were going to get the dead fish out.

"I was talking to the park ranger and he had no
idea what had happened," she said. "He said it
happened overnight. He was talking to a fisherman
who said (the pond) was fine" Saturday [10 Jul 2010].

She and her sister returned to the pond Monday
[12 Jul 2010] and the same man she believed was a
park ranger was there again. "The park ranger was
back and he said that they had unplugged one
well. There's 3 wells at the bottom of it, and
they unplugged one to see if it would help with
the oxygen flow," she said she was told.

She said she also heard a fisherman at the pond
Monday ask the man she thought was a ranger how
they were going to clean up the dead fish, and the ranger said he didn't know.

[Byline: Brandie Kessler]

