[In both cases low water oxygen and high water
temperature may be to blame. Colder water has
more dissolved oxygen, so less oxygen and higher
water temperatures can be detrimental to a variety of fish.

Large numbers of dead fish on banks and beeches
will create quite an odor. But the dead fish are
also the perfect medium for _Clostridium
botulinum_ to grow. Then the flies arrive and lay
their eggs which molt to maggots that accumulate
the botulism. Birds arrive to eat the maggots and
birds will die of botulism poisoning.

The fish will have to be picked up.

The 2nd story may be a virus, such as Koi herpes
virus. Carp are a type of Koi. However there is a
mention of perch and bass being affected, which may rule out koi herpesvirus.

However, a heat wave, especially over the eastern
seaboard of the US, including Pennsylvania has
left animals and people alike suffering. Idaho,
has not had quite the heat wave the eastern coast line has.

Photo of carp
<http://pond.dnr.cornell.edu/nyfish/Cyprinidae/common_carp.jpg> - Mod.TG]
